# 🌐 WebUI Registration UI Plan (Film-Review context)

## 🎯 Objective

Move registration from legacy standalone `/login/register.html` into the Film-Review Angular flow (`/login/film-review/#/register`) while keeping existing backend contracts unchanged and preserving current HMAC/session behavior.

This plan is for scoped integration and contract-safe migration, not auth-stack redesign.

## 👥 Role Ownership

- Film-Review routes/templates/controller wiring: `@frontend-dev`
- Registration/voucher/activation contract confirmation: `@backend-dev`
- User/email precheck behavior validation: `@backend-dev`
- Data contract checks for uniqueness/precondition semantics: `@database-dev`
- Runtime route exposure and rollout checks: `@devops`
- Shared endpoint parity impact checks: `@ios-dev`

---

## 1) Baseline and Source of Truth

Primary implementation files:
- `dalogin-quarkus/src/main/resources/META-INF/resources/film-review/app.js`
- `dalogin-quarkus/src/main/resources/META-INF/resources/film-review/templates/login.html`
- `dalogin-quarkus/src/main/resources/META-INF/resources/register.html`
- `dalogin-quarkus/src/main/resources/META-INF/resources/film-review/jsR/register.js`

Current state:
- Film-Review app has no `/register` route in `app.js`.
- Film-Review login template still points to `/login/register.html`.
- Legacy registration logic exists outside Film-Review route/template context.

Rule:
- Running servlet/controller code is source of truth if docs differ.

---

## 2) Target Registration Architecture (Film-Review first)

- Add Film-Review Angular route: `#/register`.
- Add Film-Review template under `film-review/templates` (same visual family as `login.html`).
- Keep registration flow in Film-Review Angular app context (not standalone `ng-app="hmac"` page).
- Keep legacy page temporarily for backward compatibility, but treat Film-Review route as primary entry.

---

## 3) Endpoint Contract Matrix (No contract changes)

- Username availability: `GET /mbook-1/rest/newuser/{newuser}` (`200` available, `412` taken) — trigger when username length >= 2
- Email availability: `GET /mbook-1/rest/newemail/{newemail}` (`200` available, `412` taken) — trigger only for full valid email format
- Voucher validation: `POST /login/voucher`
- Register (voucher): `POST /login/register`
- Register (no voucher): `POST /login/registerWithoutVoucher`
- Activation link handling: `GET /login/activation?activation=...`
- Activation resend handling: `POST /login/activation`

Expected UI error/success mapping:
- `200` success
- `300` activation-related flow
- `412` precondition failures
- `502` registration failure

---

## 4) Phased Implementation Strategy

### Phase P1 — Film-Review route/template migration
Focus: in-app registration experience and navigation integration.
- Add `/register` route in Film-Review `app.js`.
- Create Film-Review registration template with login-style parity.
- Update login template Sign Up link to `#/register`.

Exit criteria:
- Registration opens from Film-Review login and renders fully in Film-Review context.

### Phase P2 — Endpoint wiring and form behavior
Focus: reuse contracts with clear endpoint-specific handling.
- Wire username/email prechecks.
- Apply precheck trigger rules: username starts at 2 chars; email starts only on full email format.
- Add debounced precheck UX states (`checking`, `available`, `taken`, `unknown`) and ensure availability responses update inline field state.
- Wire voucher-first mode and no-voucher mode.
- Wire register submit with existing payload/header expectations.
- Gate submit button until all required values are valid (including precheck pass states).
- Preserve token/session behavior on successful responses.

Exit criteria:
- All registration API calls execute from Film-Review flow with expected status handling.

### Phase P3 — Activation/error hardening and compatibility
Focus: activation paths, response mapping, and rollback-safe behavior.
- Add activation handling hooks (link/resend flows where applicable).
- Normalize user-visible message mapping for `200/300/412/502`.
- Keep legacy route available during transition window.

Exit criteria:
- Activation and error handling are consistent; migration does not break existing login/session flows.

---

## 5) Validation Scope

- Field-level: username/email/password required; voucher required only in voucher mode.
- Async prechecks: debounce/trigger strategy for username/email checks to avoid noisy calls.
- Precheck UX behavior: show threshold/format hints and transient checking state before result.
- Submit gating: block submit until required values are valid (`username>=2 + available`, `full email + available`, password present, voucher present when enabled) and prechecks are not `checking`.
- Sensitive-data safety: no raw password logging in browser console.
- Route consistency: use plain hash routing (`#/register`).

---

## 6) Deliverables

- Film-Review registration template under `film-review/templates`.
- Film-Review route/controller wiring for registration in `film-review/app.js`.
- Updated registration link in `film-review/templates/login.html`.
- Endpoint mapping and phase-aligned task checklist artifacts.

---

## 7) Definition of Done (Plan-level)

- [ ] Registration template is under Film-Review template context.
- [ ] Film-Review login links to `#/register`, not `/login/register.html`.
- [ ] Username/email precheck contracts are used without backend changes.
- [ ] Username precheck starts at 2+ characters; email precheck runs only for full valid email.
- [ ] Debounced precheck UX states (`checking`, `available`, `taken`, `unknown`) are visible and consistent.
- [ ] Username/email validation responses update inline field state in the form.
- [ ] Register button remains disabled until all required values are valid and prechecks are not in-flight.
- [ ] Voucher and no-voucher registration modes are endpoint-correct.
- [ ] Activation-related behavior is handled with existing endpoint contracts.
- [ ] Response status mapping (`200/300/412/502`) is user-visible and consistent.
- [ ] Sensitive registration fields are not logged in client console.
- [ ] Ownership and phase boundaries are explicit.
